'use strict';

/* ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   MOSAIK — pixel-art dissolve puzzle (classic SameGame)

   A grid of colored pixels. Tapping a pixel selects its whole orthogonally-
   connected same-color group; if that group has ≥2 cells, the group is
   removed ("placing a container that sucks up reachable same-colored
   pixels"). Tapping an isolated (group size 1) pixel does nothing — this
   is deliberate: if singletons were removable, every board would trivially
   clear in exactly cellCount taps regardless of layout, which would gut
   the game's actual difficulty signal.

   Gravity, assumed classic SameGame two-phase (not explicitly confirmed
   beyond "pixels fall/shift" in general — a one-line rendering change if
   wrong, not a solver redesign): remaining cells in a column fall down to
   close vertical gaps; if a column becomes fully empty, columns to its
   right shift left to close the horizontal gap. The grid is represented as
   an array of bottom-up color stacks, left→right, with empty columns
   simply absent — this single representation gets BOTH gravity phases for
   free (see msApplyTap): filtering removed indices out of a column while
   keeping the rest in order IS vertical gravity, and dropping zero-length
   columns from the outer array IS horizontal compaction.

   Win condition: the entire grid cleared to empty (not "reveal a picture
   underneath" — there is no hidden image).

   Move budget: each level ships a fixed number of allowed taps, pre-
   verified solvable-to-empty within that budget. Running out of moves
   with pixels remaining is a stuck state — never persisted, always
   recomputed live (see msIsStuck) — with a toast pointing at the existing
   Restart button, same as Water Sort/Parkplatz's precedent.

   Extra-moves-via-question mechanic (mirrors Water Sort's extra-bottle /
   Parkplatz's extra-bay mechanic exactly): answering a quiz question via
   the shared askQuestions() grants +1 allowed move, capped at
   MS_MAX_EXTRA_MOVES. askQuestions() feeds the Tamagotchi automatically on
   every correct answer, same as every other question-spending flow.

   Levels are static data (MS_LEVELS below), generated offline by
   scripts/generate-mosaik-levels.js via deal-a-random-board +
   independently re-verify-with-a-real-solver + retry-on-failure (NOT a
   correct-by-construction method — see that script's header comment for
   why a clean constructive approach isn't a good fit for gravity-based
   clear games). Only the shuffled play order/position and the LIVE
   in-progress grid/move state are persisted in the save; level layouts
   ship with the app.
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

